WEBVTT

00:03.938 --> 00:04.779
Welcome to Life Church.

00:05.140 --> 00:06.001
We're so glad you're here.

00:06.642 --> 00:08.485
Life Church isn't just something you listen to.

00:08.825 --> 00:12.090
It's a place where you can grow and connect, and we want to help you do just that.

00:12.791 --> 00:20.182
Visit life.church slash podcast connect for a quick survey that will let us know more about you and the resources that would help you on your faith journey.

00:20.623 --> 00:21.584
Now, here's the message.

00:29.236 --> 00:30.918
I have a question to kick things off.

00:30.958 --> 00:33.522
How many of you are already thinking

00:33.762 --> 00:38.347
about what you want to do different to make next year better than this year.

00:38.367 --> 00:39.889
Show hands, how many of you?

00:39.909 --> 00:40.690
Okay, pretty much all of us.

00:41.431 --> 00:44.935
For me, I've got like one very clear and specific goal.

00:46.717 --> 00:51.202
And when I tell you what this goal is, I already know that you're going to judge me.

00:52.663 --> 00:55.246
But when you do, not if, when you do, that's okay.

00:55.687 --> 01:00.232
Because God loves me, my wife loves me, my mom is here and she loves me.

01:00.272 --> 01:02.194
This is the goal.

01:02.914 --> 01:04.596
to beat up my little brother.

01:05.917 --> 01:09.841
Now I know, you're thinking, wow, that is weirdly specific and not very Christian.

01:10.201 --> 01:11.762
I told you you would judge me.

01:12.163 --> 01:13.524
But listen to this, let me explain, let me explain.

01:13.544 --> 01:16.267
This is the context for this goal.

01:16.287 --> 01:18.189
I come from a family of fighters.

01:18.689 --> 01:25.836
So my dad, he was a fifth degree black belt in Taekwondo, a brown belt in Judo, a blue belt in Jiu Jitsu, and a stud of a wrestler in high school.

01:25.856 --> 01:32.242
I started training back when I was going into my freshman year of high school, and my little brother started when he was even younger than that.

01:32.418 --> 01:36.685
And so for my entire life, I have whooped on my little brother.

01:38.788 --> 01:41.512
But in the last few years, some things have changed.

01:42.774 --> 01:50.226
In the last few years, my little brother has transformed from a boy into a beast of a man.

01:50.847 --> 01:52.689
He is a freak of nature.

01:52.729 --> 01:55.093
He's currently in the army training for special forces.

01:55.374 --> 01:58.258
That means that every day, all day, he eats,

01:58.370 --> 02:02.836
He breathes and he sleeps, becoming the baddest human on the planet.

02:04.518 --> 02:06.942
And in the last few years, I turned 30.

02:07.522 --> 02:08.644
We had our second kid.

02:08.664 --> 02:12.569
I had a whole bunch of other life responsibilities fall on my plate.

02:16.074 --> 02:22.082
And so now, last couple of times we've scuffled, he has come out on top.

02:22.102 --> 02:24.786
But I'm telling you, ladies and gentlemen, there is a chance

02:25.026 --> 02:36.078
that if the same spirit that raised Jesus from the dead is living inside of me, there is a chance that just one more time I can beat my little brother in a fight.

02:37.639 --> 02:39.641
Very small chance.

02:39.721 --> 02:48.090
But for me, having that as my goal helps me make the process of being physically healthy way more enjoyable.

02:48.110 --> 02:51.794
Now hopefully for you, whatever your habits that you're wanting to set,

02:52.034 --> 02:55.621
the resolutions that you're thinking about, the goals that you're attempting to achieve.

02:55.881 --> 03:00.289
Hopefully for you, those are more realistic and more beneficial than mine.

03:01.411 --> 03:07.743
Maybe for you, the thing that you wanna do is get physically healthy so that you can play with your kids and not be in pain.

03:08.584 --> 03:11.730
Maybe for you, you wanna grow spiritually stronger.

03:11.842 --> 03:15.147
so that you can experience the presence of God in a new and a different way.

03:15.668 --> 03:25.103
Maybe for you, the thing that you want is to attack your debt so that you can experience financial freedom, or maybe you wanna strengthen your relationships.

03:25.123 --> 03:29.130
So you're already thinking about how you can be a more intentional friend.

03:29.891 --> 03:36.722
Whatever it is, there will come a point where all of us, our discipline runs out.

03:36.742 --> 03:39.506
Our desires to do the right thing reach zero.

03:39.906 --> 03:43.851
And statistically speaking, that most often happens on the second Friday of January.

03:44.131 --> 03:47.015
That's why that Friday has become known as Quitters Day.

03:47.315 --> 03:52.281
Because that is the day when the vast majority of people quit their New Year's resolutions.

03:53.262 --> 04:00.471
And so if we wanna make change that lasts, I think one of the best things that we can do is confront the brutal facts.

04:00.491 --> 04:03.815
That knowing better is not the same thing as doing better.

04:04.276 --> 04:07.019
That knowing better is not the same thing as doing better.

04:07.359 --> 04:09.522
If it was, we'd all be crushing it.

04:10.050 --> 04:13.875
Because to be physically healthy means exercising and eating better.

04:14.255 --> 04:17.740
To be financially successful means making more and spending less.

04:18.020 --> 04:23.407
Being spiritually strong comes from time in the word and worshiping alongside God's people.

04:23.727 --> 04:24.909
We all know those things.

04:27.172 --> 04:32.759
But for most of us, we aren't actually experiencing those things, at least not consistently.

04:33.600 --> 04:38.706
And so my recommendation, if you want to make change sustainable,

04:39.458 --> 04:42.262
is figure out how to make the process more enjoyable.

04:42.282 --> 04:47.550
If you want change to be sustainable, make the process enjoyable.

04:48.251 --> 04:58.286
For me, when I first started eating healthy, it was miserable because I thought eating healthy meant only eating the most bland and tasteless foods imaginable.

04:58.646 --> 05:09.202
I'm talking baked chicken, I'm talking steamed broccoli, I'm talking brown rice, I'm talking spinach and lettuce salads with no sauce or seasoning to speak of.

05:09.922 --> 05:14.808
And so after doing that for a little bit of time, it was miserable and I wanted to throw in the towel.

05:16.410 --> 05:24.982
And then somebody showed me that you can eat food that is good for you and also taste good.

05:25.703 --> 05:32.111
They're like, healthy food can be tasty and it doesn't take forever to make and it doesn't cost you a second mortgage to afford.

05:32.451 --> 05:37.458
That if you eat healthy in a way that is enjoyable, it becomes more sustainable.

05:38.306 --> 05:47.016
And so if we want to make lasting change going into this new year, I think one of the best things that we can do is figure out how to make the process enjoyable.

05:47.497 --> 05:58.810
Now out of all the changes, all the habits, all the goals, all the resolutions that we could set, I believe there is one that has the power to make a bigger difference in your life and faith than anything else.

05:59.351 --> 06:05.138
And that one habit, that one change is this, to read the Bible more days than you don't.

06:05.634 --> 06:08.718
Read the Bible more days than you don't.

06:08.738 --> 06:10.520
Now, you don't just have to take my word for it.

06:10.940 --> 06:13.663
There's this organization, they're the Center for Bible Engagement.

06:13.984 --> 06:20.912
And after studying the lives of more than 100,000 people, they discovered what they call the rule of four.

06:21.372 --> 06:32.946
And it's this idea that if somebody reads the Bible zero times a week, one time a week, two times a week, or even three times a week, there is little to no change in their life.

06:33.442 --> 06:43.636
But as soon as somebody reads it four or more days a week, more days than they don't, the changes become noticeable and measurable.

06:44.117 --> 06:44.638
Here's what they found.

06:44.678 --> 06:50.346
Those who read the Bible four or more days a week are 228% more likely to share their faith.

06:50.606 --> 06:53.690
They're more than 400% more likely to memorize Scripture.

06:53.871 --> 07:00.179
They are 59% less likely to watch porn, and they are 30% less likely to struggle with loneliness.

07:00.380 --> 07:02.002
And this is just the beginning.

07:02.082 --> 07:13.073
Because those who read the Bible four or more days a week, they are less tempted to overeat, have sex outside of marriage, neglect their family, lie, lash out in anger, drink excessively, gossip, or overspend.

07:13.093 --> 07:21.122
When you read the Bible more days than you don't, we get more of what we want and less of what we don't.

07:21.142 --> 07:24.906
That's why to summarize their findings, this is what they said.

07:24.946 --> 07:29.170
They said that engaging the Bible four or more days a week

07:29.346 --> 07:39.516
is the single most powerful predictor of spiritual growth, which they define as becoming more like Christ in our thoughts, our words, and our deeds.

07:40.216 --> 07:47.704
So if you want next year to be better than this year, I think one of the best things that you can do is read the Bible more days than you don't.

07:48.324 --> 07:53.449
And all of this lines up so beautifully with what God's word actually says about itself.

07:54.010 --> 07:56.312
In 2 Timothy chapter three, Paul wrote these words.

07:56.933 --> 07:58.514
He says that all scripture

07:58.850 --> 07:59.691
is God-breathed.

08:00.231 --> 08:10.462
It is useful for teaching, rebuking, correcting, and training and righteousness so that the servant of God may be thoroughly equipped for every good work.

08:11.243 --> 08:20.111
So ladies and gentlemen, if you want to make next year better than this one, choose to read the Bible more days than you don't.

08:20.132 --> 08:26.578
Now, if all it took to do better was to know better, then we could just end the sermon right here and all go home.

08:27.938 --> 08:30.863
but because that's not how change actually works.

08:31.524 --> 08:40.139
What I wanna do for the rest of our time is talk about how to make reading the Bible more enjoyable so that it will be more sustainable.

08:40.560 --> 08:45.408
So if you wanna make reading the Bible more enjoyable, I think the first thing you should do is know the goal.

08:46.109 --> 08:48.654
Know the goal of why we read God's word.

08:49.315 --> 08:53.522
I don't care who you are, but winning is always more fun than losing.

08:54.434 --> 09:03.585
And I think for so many people, the reason we walk away from our time in God's word, not having enjoyed it, is because we don't actually know if we're winning or not.

09:03.605 --> 09:05.487
Thing number two, find a guide.

09:06.008 --> 09:10.493
Because making progress always feels better than being stuck.

09:11.134 --> 09:17.722
And if you wanna get unstuck, one of the wisest things that you can do is find a guide to help you get where you want to go.

09:18.263 --> 09:21.567
And then thing number three, refuse to give up.

09:22.288 --> 09:24.210
Refuse to give up.

09:24.386 --> 09:34.138
because the joy of overcoming a significant challenge is almost always worth the effort it took to get there.

09:34.158 --> 09:42.628
But if you stop before you get there, you don't get to experience the joy that is waiting for you.

09:42.648 --> 09:54.002
Now, I'm aware that at this point, there might be some of you thinking, okay, I hear all that, but it sounds like you're still just trying to get me to eat healthy food, like chicken, rice, and broccoli.

09:54.082 --> 09:55.524
Let me be clear, 1000%.

09:56.085 --> 09:57.887
You have to still eat the healthy stuff.

09:58.348 --> 09:59.770
You actually have to read God's Word.

10:00.010 --> 10:05.318
That's why I'm not trying to convince you that I can help you make reading God's Word the most enjoyable thing you can do.

10:07.120 --> 10:09.924
But we can make it more enjoyable.

10:09.944 --> 10:10.905
It's still gonna take work.

10:11.526 --> 10:13.248
It's still gonna take some discipline.

10:13.289 --> 10:20.178
For me personally, I have eaten lots of healthy chicken sandwiches, but none of them taste better than the spicy chicken from Chick-fil-A.

10:21.346 --> 10:28.919
But because I know what some healthy chicken sandwiches can taste like, the spicy chicken is less tempting.

10:28.939 --> 10:33.226
And the healthy ones are more enjoyable so I can keep coming back to them.

10:34.328 --> 10:36.552
That's what I want to try to do with the Bible.

10:37.353 --> 10:47.570
Help you make reading it more enjoyable so that as you do, you will experience the change that is available and you will want to keep coming back for more.

10:47.746 --> 10:53.052
Now, for me, when I first started reading the Bible after I became a Christian, I did not know the goal.

10:53.973 --> 10:55.355
I did not have a guide.

10:56.215 --> 11:04.124
But because Jesus had changed my life and because of the discipline instilled in me by my parents, I just kept showing up.

11:04.745 --> 11:06.767
I refused to give up.

11:06.887 --> 11:09.711
I mentioned that I started training martial arts when I was in high school.

11:10.091 --> 11:16.338
And there were so many days, even though I loved it, where I would much rather sit at home and play Xbox.

11:16.482 --> 11:18.384
then actually go to practice.

11:18.404 --> 11:26.932
And every time my dad would say the same thing, he'd look me in the eyes and say, son, bring your body and your mind will follow.

11:26.952 --> 11:29.435
Bring your body and your mind will follow.

11:29.955 --> 11:40.145
Because he understood that the joy that we experience after we do the thing outweighs us not wanting to do the thing before we actually do the thing.

11:41.006 --> 11:45.330
And so when I first became a Christian, I got my great grandmother's King James Version Bible.

11:46.370 --> 12:02.868
And every night, for 30 minutes, for three months, I brought my body, and my mind kind of followed, because the truth is, I was having such a hard time actually following along with what I was reading, because I understood none of it.

12:03.449 --> 12:07.353
No, no, for some of you, KJV, that is your cup of tea, it is not mine.

12:08.515 --> 12:15.122
But thankfully, I had a guide, I had a pastor, and I went to him and I said, hey man, I need some help, because this Bible

12:15.202 --> 12:16.784
might be the worst book I've ever read.

12:17.846 --> 12:22.834
And he recommended something that might be just like common information for all of you.

12:22.894 --> 12:24.657
It was not for me as a brand new baby Christian.

12:25.318 --> 12:27.401
He said, did you know there are other Bible versions?

12:29.083 --> 12:36.835
And all of a sudden, my Bible reading became less miserable, not yet quite enjoyable.

12:36.855 --> 12:43.666
And then the real shift happened about six years ago when I changed my role at the church instead of being a youth pastor at a single location.

12:43.778 --> 12:47.021
I was put in charge of overseeing the content for our whole student ministry.

12:47.482 --> 12:53.588
And with that responsibility, like I now had to figure out, okay, like what is this book really?

12:55.010 --> 12:56.271
Why do we trust it?

12:57.012 --> 12:58.894
And how do we read it wisely?

12:58.914 --> 13:01.636
And so I just dove head first into all of those questions.

13:02.157 --> 13:08.443
And as I was trying to become a better Bible teacher, God showed me how to be a better Bible reader.

13:09.364 --> 13:11.026
And that's when for me,

13:11.234 --> 13:17.062
Reading the Bible finally started to become enjoyable because I knew the goal.

13:17.723 --> 13:21.949
I found some guides and I refused to give up.

13:23.692 --> 13:35.669
And so all of that being said, what I wanna do next is a little bit different, but I wanna try to the best of my ability, help you see the goodness of God's word.

13:36.290 --> 13:39.154
The stuff that has always been there,

13:40.226 --> 13:42.688
but for most of us we haven't seen before.

13:43.309 --> 13:56.602
And so I want you to think of my role as kind of like a server at a fancy restaurant where the chef has put in all of this really fancy stuff to make this meal extra tasty, extra good.

13:57.243 --> 14:07.092
And I just wanna explain to you what God put into his word to show you just how intentional he was with every word.

14:07.412 --> 14:09.074
Now, disclaimer number one,

14:09.602 --> 14:10.343
We're gonna go fast.

14:10.363 --> 14:22.619
They're gonna put a 10 minute timer on the screen to keep me on track because if they let me, I would talk about this all day, but we got another church service coming so we're gonna stay on track.

14:23.240 --> 14:28.667
The other thing is if you're a note taker, you better write fast because we will be moving fast.

14:28.687 --> 14:31.290
Now if you are not, I need you to know, that's totally okay.

14:31.310 --> 14:37.298
Like if you go to a fancy restaurant, you can enjoy the meal without paying any attention to what the server says about it.

14:37.666 --> 14:46.434
You can enjoy God's word without understanding anything that I'm about to tell you, but hopefully this will help you appreciate it just a little bit more.

14:47.195 --> 14:50.318
So that for you, reading it will be a little bit more enjoyable.

14:50.959 --> 14:53.641
And as a result, become a little bit more sustainable.

14:54.382 --> 14:59.987
So in three, two, one, let's go.

15:00.708 --> 15:07.314
I need the best way to show off the goodness of God's word is to go all the way to the beginning in Genesis.

15:07.458 --> 15:08.079
Chapter one.

15:08.780 --> 15:09.361
For a couple reasons.

15:09.781 --> 15:11.223
Number one, that's where God started.

15:11.944 --> 15:13.867
That's where most people start reading the Bible.

15:13.907 --> 15:21.477
And this is also the place where so many new believers and skeptics get tripped up with questions.

15:21.938 --> 15:32.533
Because right at the beginning, they are forced to ask the question, do I trust what God has said or all the stuff that I learned growing up in school?

15:33.133 --> 15:36.498
Because it seems like these ideas are contradicting each other.

15:37.922 --> 15:44.690
And I think it seems like that because for the vast majority of people, they don't actually know the goal of reading the Bible.

15:45.771 --> 15:51.058
If nobody's ever told you this, the goal of the Bible is not to answer every question about everything.

15:51.078 --> 15:52.840
That's not what the goal is.

15:53.521 --> 16:01.150
The goal is to introduce us to God, to help us understand who He is and how we are meant to relate to Him.

16:01.811 --> 16:07.698
The reason I know that is because that's where the entire book begins in the beginning.

16:08.066 --> 16:10.248
God, he's the main character.

16:10.809 --> 16:13.152
He created the heavens and the earth.

16:13.492 --> 16:19.719
And the entire rest of the biblical story is explaining God's relationship with his creation.

16:20.560 --> 16:23.584
So if you wanna read the Bible wisely, I got two big ideas for you.

16:23.604 --> 16:26.146
Number one, remember that Jesus is king.

16:26.667 --> 16:29.851
That means every page and every passage is pointing us to Jesus.

16:30.131 --> 16:32.654
And it is showing us how we're meant to live like Jesus.

16:33.094 --> 16:36.338
And idea number two is that context is everything.

16:36.610 --> 16:45.564
Context, all the information that gives meaning to what we are reading helps us understand what we're reading and what it means.

16:45.584 --> 16:47.868
So let's talk about the context of Genesis chapter one.

16:48.849 --> 16:59.546
This chapter was originally written down by Moses and delivered to the Jewish people who at this point in history were wandering through the wilderness on their way to the Promised Land.

17:00.127 --> 17:01.810
And right before this,

17:02.018 --> 17:07.124
These people had spent 400 years as slaves in Egypt.

17:07.685 --> 17:15.073
That means for generation after generation, they had been born into, they had lived under, and they had died as slaves.

17:16.195 --> 17:20.840
Slaves to the whims of Pharaoh, a man who claimed to be a God.

17:22.222 --> 17:25.446
And in all of a sudden, a new God shows up.

17:26.447 --> 17:29.170
And through his human partner, a guy named Moses,

17:29.378 --> 17:39.273
He begins doing miraculous things, a series of 10 demonstrations, every single one of them precisely aimed at undermining the authority of the Egyptian gods.

17:39.533 --> 17:42.297
He was sending a message the entire time.

17:42.518 --> 17:53.554
And so now all of a sudden, you've got these people who had only ever known Egypt, and now they're being asked to follow God, a God who is leading them

17:53.794 --> 18:01.742
with his visible presence, a pillar of smoke in the day, a pillar of fire at night, who is taking them to a new place they've never been before.

18:02.002 --> 18:04.565
So the questions they were asking were not.

18:05.626 --> 18:07.368
So like, how old is the earth really?

18:08.329 --> 18:11.512
And is all this stuff supposed to be literal or is it metaphor?

18:12.213 --> 18:14.535
They were asking the question, who is this God?

18:15.836 --> 18:21.522
And what makes us so special that he would go to such great lengths to save us?

18:22.178 --> 18:23.679
And we keep reading in Genesis 1.

18:24.220 --> 18:29.085
The next few verses start to show us a little bit about what God is doing.

18:29.765 --> 18:34.470
In verse three, we see that God said, let there be light.

18:35.011 --> 18:38.094
Now 10 times in Genesis 1, we read God said.

18:38.694 --> 18:41.557
And 10 times what God says comes to pass.

18:42.458 --> 18:45.721
After he says, let there be light, God saw that the light was good.

18:46.062 --> 18:50.546
Seven times in Genesis 1, God sees it and he calls it good.

18:51.714 --> 18:53.737
and he separates the light from the darkness.

18:54.078 --> 18:56.521
God calls the light day and the darkness he calls night.

18:56.862 --> 18:59.746
There was evening and there was morning the first day.

19:00.187 --> 19:02.150
This is the first of seven days.

19:02.710 --> 19:12.124
Now, if you wanna understand Hebrew poetry wisely, you gotta pay attention to the patterns and the problems because those reveal the purpose.

19:12.144 --> 19:17.733
So we see these patterns start to emerge right here in the beginning that God says it and it comes to pass.

19:18.213 --> 19:21.298
That God sees what he has made and he calls it

19:21.506 --> 19:24.289
Good, the first of seven days.

19:25.129 --> 19:31.756
But there's already a problem because that refrain evening and morning only shows up six times.

19:32.536 --> 19:34.438
The pattern breaks.

19:34.458 --> 19:34.678
Why?

19:35.539 --> 19:38.162
Because there's something really special about the seventh day.

19:38.682 --> 19:46.810
If we go to the next page in Genesis chapter two, we're told that by the seventh day, God had finished the work He had been doing.

19:47.230 --> 19:51.154
So on the seventh day, He rested from all of His work.

19:51.426 --> 19:59.399
Then God blessed the seventh day He made it holy because on it He rested from all the work of creating that He had done.

19:59.439 --> 20:04.707
Every other day gets mentioned one time, but the seventh day is mentioned three times.

20:05.328 --> 20:09.054
And three times we're told on this day God rested.

20:09.315 --> 20:09.936
He finished.

20:10.216 --> 20:11.799
He stopped working.

20:12.760 --> 20:18.770
Now for most of us, this doesn't really mean much of anything because we've always had a two-day weekend.

20:20.290 --> 20:21.792
but for the original audience.

20:22.572 --> 20:28.778
Remember, for 400 years, all they had ever known was work.

20:28.798 --> 20:30.740
Day in and day out.

20:31.381 --> 20:42.192
All they had ever known was slavery to Pharaoh and to the Egyptian gods, who in their worldview, the people of God, the Hebrew people, they were nothing more than worms.

20:44.254 --> 20:48.338
But then all of a sudden, God shows up in power.

20:49.090 --> 20:51.914
and after he leads them into this new place.

20:52.394 --> 20:59.643
As he tells them about these promises that he has for them, they discover that he is a God who rests.

21:00.885 --> 21:03.568
He's a God who created them in his image.

21:04.129 --> 21:09.075
And when God saw humanity, he called them very good.

21:10.417 --> 21:18.066
You see, what Genesis 1 is telling us is that God is a God of love, who creates everything and it is always good.

21:18.722 --> 21:22.507
And he invites us as human beings to partner with him in his good plans for the world.

21:23.088 --> 21:25.391
And so on the seventh day, God rests.

21:25.411 --> 21:32.360
This would set the pattern of the Sabbath where once a week the Jewish people would stop working.

21:33.121 --> 21:34.803
And it's more than just a day off.

21:35.364 --> 21:39.309
It is an invitation to rest in the hand of an Almighty God.

21:39.930 --> 21:46.258
It is an invitation to believe deep in your bones that your value does not come from what you do.

21:46.850 --> 21:49.254
Your value comes from the God who made you.

21:51.857 --> 21:56.604
And that truth that showed all the way up in Genesis 1 is still true for you today.

21:57.526 --> 21:59.308
